          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Host city</th><th>Country</th><th>Stadium</th><th>Airport(s)</th><th>Group</th><th>Knockout</th><th>Total</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>{hostCities.map((city) => <tr><td>{city.city}</td><td>{city.country}</td><td>{city.stadium}</td><td>{city.airportCodes.join(', ')}</td><td>{city.groupMatches}</td><td>{city.knockoutMatches}</td><td><strong>{city.matches}</strong></td></tr>)}</tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="table-caption"><strong>Table 1.</strong> Host-city match allocations and associated major commercial gateways. Source: FIFA official schedule.</p>

        <section>
          <h2>Host Cities and Airport Baselines</h2>
          <p>Baseline airport scale shows why an identical match-day pulse would not have an identical operational meaning everywhere. ATL recorded 52.5 million enplanements in 2024, compared with 5.9 million at MCI. DFW handled 42.4 million; IAH handled 23.3 million before adding Hobby's 7.1 million. Large volume can provide more routes and recovery options, but it also means event traffic enters an already dense schedule.</p>
          <p>This baseline does not measure spare capacity. A large airport may absorb additional passengers efficiently, while a smaller airport may have more available gates at a particular hour. It does, however, identify where World Cup flows intersect with the largest existing passenger systems.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="chart-figure">
          <div class="chart-title"><span>CY2024 revenue passenger enplanements</span><strong>FAA pre-event baseline</strong></div>
          <div class="bar-chart">{comparisonAirports.map((airport) => <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label">{airport.airport}</span><div class="bar-track"><span style={`width:${Number(airport.cy2024_enplanements) / maxAirportVolume * 100}%`}></span></div><strong>{formatMillions(airport.cy2024_enplanements)}</strong></div>)}</div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 2.</strong> Departing revenue passengers at selected host-city airports. This is an annual 2024 baseline, not World Cup traffic and not aircraft operations. <span>Source: FAA CY2024 ACAIS commercial-service enplanements.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Hub Airports and Network Pressure</h2>
          <p>Hub-and-spoke airlines redistribute passengers from many origins through connecting airports. ATL, DFW, and IAH are both host-city gateways and transfer hubs. ORD, DEN, and CLT are not host cities, but their schedules can feed passengers toward several tournament markets. This creates reach and flexibility while coupling operations across cities.</p>
          <p><strong>The World Cup turns the airline network into a live stress test: when one hub slows down, delays can quickly spread across the system.</strong> A late inbound aircraft can create missed connections, delay its next departure, and displace passengers onto later flights. This mechanism is well established, but the charts below show exposure rather than causation.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="chart-figure index-figure">
          <div class="chart-title"><span>Exploratory pressure index</span><strong>0-100 screening score</strong></div>
          <div class="bar-chart">{pressure.map((row) => <div class="bar-row"><span class="bar-label city">{row.rank}. {row.host_city}</span><div class="bar-track"><span style={`width:${row.pressure_index}%`}></span></div><strong>{row.pressure_index}</strong></div>)}</div>
          <div class="formula">100 × (normalized matches + normalized metro enplanements + FAA hub score) / 3</div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 3.</strong> A transparent, equal-weight exploratory index. It suggests where tournament load and baseline network scale overlap; it does not predict delay or capacity failure. <span>Sources: FIFA schedule; FAA CY2024 ACAIS; calculations by author.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section class="beyond-demand">
          <p class="eyebrow">Beyond demand</p>
          <h2>Beyond Demand: Additional Network Effects</h2>
          <p>Passenger totals alone miss how tournament travel is routed. The World Cup can temporarily reshape the network through alliance-linked connections, one-way fan movement, overlap with the summer peak, and reduced recovery capacity during convective weather.</p>

          <h3>Airline Alliances and Hub Dependence</h3>
          <p>World Cup travel may follow airline partnership structures as well as geography. Germany-related traffic, for example, can use Lufthansa and United within Star Alliance, making IAH, ORD, EWR, DEN, and SFO plausible transfer points. SkyTeam connections can concentrate some European and Latin American flows through ATL or JFK, while oneworld itineraries can link LHR, MAD, or DOH with American Airlines gateways such as DFW and MIA.</p>
          <p>This is not an itinerary forecast. National team, fan origin, fare, nonstop availability, partnership schedules, and connecting-airport structure all affect routing. Equal numbers of supporters from different countries may therefore enter the U.S. network through different hubs.</p>
          <div class="alliance-flow" role="img" aria-label="Conceptual airline alliance flows from international gateways through United States hubs">
            <div><strong>Star Alliance</strong><span>FRA / MUC</span><i>-&gt;</i><span>IAH / ORD / EWR / DEN / SFO</span></div>
            <div><strong>SkyTeam</strong><span>Europe / Latin America</span><i>-&gt;</i><span>ATL / JFK</span></div>
            <div><strong>oneworld</strong><span>LHR / MAD / DOH</span><i>-&gt;</i><span>DFW / MIA</span></div>
          </div>
          <p class="concept-caption">Conceptual alliance-linked gateways. Actual itineraries depend on schedules, fares, and nonstop service.</p>

          <h3>Temporary Fan Mobility Corridors</h3>
          <p>Normal leisure and business travel is often modeled as a round trip: A to B and back to A. Supporters following a team can instead produce an open chain: home country to Host City 1 to Host City 2 to a possible knockout city, then home. Germany-related travel might begin in Germany, reach Houston for the Curaçao match, continue to another group-stage host, and branch again after qualification.</p>
          <div class="corridor-flow" role="img" aria-label="Temporary fan mobility corridor from Germany through Houston to later World Cup host cities">
            <span><small>Origin</small>Germany</span><i>-&gt;</i><span class="active"><small>Group stage</small>Houston</span><i>-&gt;</i><span><small>Next fixture</small>Host City 2</span><i>-&gt;</i><span><small>Conditional</small>Knockout city</span>
          </div>
          <p class="concept-caption">One-way tournament chasing can create directional seat demand that does not balance neatly in reverse.</p>

          <h3>World Cup Meets the U.S. Summer Travel Peak</h3>
          <p>Airlines and airports are not managing the tournament in isolation. They are handling normal summer demand, World Cup demand, international visitors, and domestic fan travel at the same time. Aircraft, gates, crews, and rebooking capacity already committed to the seasonal peak cannot be added instantly. Resilience therefore matters as much as the event's net passenger increase.</p>

          <h3>Weather and Delay Propagation Risk</h3>
          <p>June and July bring thunderstorms to Houston, Atlanta, Florida, and broad parts of the central and eastern United States. Convective weather can reduce arrival rates, close ramp areas, or force reroutes at ATL, IAH, MIA, DFW, ORD, and DEN. Because these airports connect many itineraries, a local constraint can affect several host cities.</p>
          <p><strong>World Cup demand may not create delays by itself, but it can reduce the system's ability to absorb weather-driven disruptions.</strong> When later flights are already full, a missed connection is harder to recover; when aircraft and crews are tightly utilized, one delayed rotation can travel farther through the schedule.</p>
        </section>

        <figure class="dark-figure flow-figure">
          <div class="weather-chain" role="img" aria-label="Summer thunderstorms lead to hub disruption, missed connections, and downstream host-city delays"><span>Summer thunderstorms<small>Houston / Atlanta / Florida / central U.S.</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Hub airport disruption<small>ATL / IAH / MIA / DFW / ORD / DEN</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Missed connections<small>Passengers, aircraft, and crews displaced</small></span><i>↓</i><span>Downstream host-city delays<small>Effects spread beyond the weather airport</small></span></div>
          <figcaption><strong>Figure 4.</strong> Conceptual weather-delay propagation through major hubs. The diagram describes a mechanism; it does not report observed World Cup delay. <span>Author's diagram informed by hub-and-spoke operations.</span></figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section>
          <h2>Houston Case Study</h2>
          <p>I attended Germany versus Curaçao at Houston Stadium on June 14. The match turned Houston from an abstract map node into a practical example of layered transportation demand: international and domestic arrivals entered through IAH and Hobby, visitors accumulated downtown, and a large crowd converged on one stadium district at a fixed time.</p>
          <p>Even a group-stage match involving one major football nation generated a crowd concentration comparable to major U.S. sporting events. This kind of short-term concentration creates transportation demand beyond the stadium itself, affecting airports, hotels, rideshare networks, and public transportation.</p>
          <p>Official baseline data puts the airport system in context. IAH and HOU recorded 30.5 million combined enplanements in 2024, while Houston's seven matches include two knockout fixtures. FAA event guidance also imposed Prior Permission Required procedures for area airports and warned pilots to expect traffic-management initiatives. Those facts indicate potential concentration; they do not prove that the match caused a particular commercial delay.</p>
          <p>At the time of observation, IAH showed elevated delay conditions, including an average reported delay of 73 minutes. This does not prove that the World Cup caused the delay, but it illustrates the type of operational pressure that large hub airports can face during periods of elevated travel demand.</p>

          <h3>Demand Waves, Not Just Demand Spikes</h3>
          <p>Houston's aviation pressure was not limited to the hours around one kickoff. The Germany-Curaçao match on June 14 generated an arrival wave before the match and a departure wave afterward. On June 15, when I departed, thunderstorm activity added operational uncertainty while supporters, media personnel, and other visitors were leaving the city. Two days later, Houston hosted Portugal versus DR Congo, bringing another cycle of fan arrivals, team logistics, media movement, and airport activity.</p>
          <p>This pattern is different from a one-day mega-event such as the Super Bowl. A Super Bowl can create a very large but comparatively concentrated arrival-event-departure cycle. A World Cup host city manages repeated cycles across several matchdays. One wave may still be departing while teams, sponsors, media crews, and supporters associated with the next match are arriving.</p>
          <p>The operational problem is therefore cumulative. Airport staff, gates, ground transportation, hotels, and airline recovery capacity must absorb recurring peaks while weather remains uncertain. An individual wave may be manageable, but closely spaced waves leave less time for the system to reset.</p>

          <div class="demand-waves" role="img" aria-label="Houston timeline showing the Germany versus Curaçao match, departures and thunderstorm activity with observed airport delays, followed by arrivals and logistics for Portugal versus DR Congo">
            <h4>Demand Waves and Operational Stress in Houston</h4>
            <span><small>June 14</small>Germany vs. Curaçao</span><i>↓</i>
            <span><small>June 15</small>Fan departures + thunderstorm activity</span><i>↓</i>
            <span class="observed"><small>Field observation</small>Elevated IAH delay conditions</span><i>↓</i>
            <span><small>June 17</small>Portugal vs. DR Congo arrivals and logistics</span>
          </div>
          <p class="concept-caption">The sequence illustrates recurring demand and operational waves. It does not attribute the observed delay to the tournament.</p>
          <p class="field-note">Field observations are used here as contextual evidence rather than causal proof.</p>
        </section>

