        <section>
          <h2>Uneven Impact Across Cities</h2>
          <p>The pressure index ranks New York/New Jersey, Dallas, and Atlanta highest because each combines many matches with a large airport system and hub status. Kansas City ranks lower because MCI's passenger baseline is smaller, but that should not be read as “no pressure.” A smaller system can still face sharp peaks, limited nonstop options, or business-aviation parking constraints.</p>
          <p>Demand evidence is also uneven. Sojern reported April booking growth of 42% for Dallas and 38% for Houston, but a 16% decline for Seattle. Reuters later reported that high ticket prices and complex international travel weakened the expected benefit for some U.S. airlines and hotels. The data suggests concentration and mismatch, not a uniform continental surge.</p>
          <p>Business aviation adds another layer. NBAA advises operators to secure required reservations and expect holding or surface delays; Universal Weather identifies slot, parking, permit, and security pressure. FAA procedures coordinate scarce airspace and ramp access through flight-plan windows, ground-delay programs, TFRs, and airport-specific permissions.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="research-projects">
          <p class="eyebrow">Ongoing research agenda</p>
          <h2>Connecting This Blog to My Aviation Projects</h2>
          <p>This article extends three existing projects rather than treating the tournament as an isolated event. Together, they move from the structure of the airline network, to the historical analysis of disruption, to operational monitoring. The World Cup supplies a time-bounded stress test in which those layers interact.</p>

          <div class="project-evidence-grid">
            <article class="project-evidence">
              <img src={`${base}project-previews/hub-atlas.svg`} alt="Stylized route-map preview of the U.S. Airline Hub Atlas" loading="lazy" />
              <div>
                <p class="project-number">01 / Network structure</p>
                <h3><a href="https://yuhexin25-oss.github.io/us-airline-hub-atlas/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">U.S. Airline Hub Atlas</a></h3>
                <p>The atlas scales airport nodes with FAA CY2024 enplanements and uses a static OpenFlights route snapshot to expose airport hierarchy, carrier networks, and concentrated connectivity. Its central insight supports this article directly: traffic does not enter an evenly connected national grid. It is organized through a limited set of major hubs and focus cities.</p>
                <p>That structure helps explain why World Cup exposure concentrates at ATL, DFW, IAH, EWR, DEN, ORD, and SFO. A hub offers more destination choices and recovery paths, but dependence on that same node allows disruption to reach many downstream routes.</p>
              </div>
            </article>

            <article class="project-evidence">
              <img src={`${base}project-previews/flight-delay.svg`} alt="Stylized dashboard preview of the U.S. Flight Delay Analysis project" loading="lazy" />
              <div>
                <p class="project-number">02 / Historical analysis framework</p>
                <h3><a href="https://yuhexin25-oss.github.io/usflightdelay/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">U.S. Flight Delay Analysis</a></h3>
                <p>FlightScope organizes delay questions by airport concentration, hub-versus-regional performance, route disruption, delay cause, carrier, and seasonality. Those dimensions define how the World Cup should be evaluated after the event: not only by average delay, but by where disruption clustered and how it moved through connected routes.</p>
                <p>The current site is explicitly a mock BTS-style research prototype, not a source of observed historical results. Its value here is methodological: it specifies the comparisons that real BTS On-Time Performance data can support when measuring hub vulnerability and disruption transmission.</p>
              </div>
            </article>

            <article class="project-evidence">
              <img src={`${base}project-previews/route-risk.svg`} alt="Stylized route-risk preview of the Hub Resilience Monitor" loading="lazy" />
