        </section>

        <section>
          <h2>Conclusion: A Stress Test of Existing Vulnerabilities</h2>
          <p>The 2026 FIFA World Cup is not just creating more aviation demand. It is exposing deeper questions about how the U.S. aviation network handles stress: hub dependency, alliance geography, one-way fan mobility, summer travel peaks, weather disruption, and delay propagation.</p>
          <p>The tournament provides a useful natural experiment because its match schedule creates known demand events across different airport systems. After the event, FAA OPSNET and BTS TranStats can test where traffic and delay became unusual, how quickly airports recovered, and whether disruption traveled through connecting hubs. The value of that work is not another technical demonstration. It is a clearer understanding of where passengers and regions remain vulnerable when a tightly connected transportation system is asked to absorb an exceptional event.</p>
        </section>

